in attempt to claw a dove grey sky,I could lay here, let the numbing cold take my body. My body was an extension of my soul, my blade an extension of my body. I turned it over slowly in my hand, studying its gleem intently. If it gleems then so does my soul? War, the only place I felt comfortable, real, ironicly was in the struggle of life and death. Like the great Warlord himself who had all the Gods turn against him, I too could taste the bitter herbs of the collected nations of the world. How was it that I stood? Why did I insist on continuing? What was this journey, and its remarkably importance that it could not be released? What was I preserving, and to what end? <br>
<br>
I had lost my way sometime ago in these frozen waste lands, I was no Ranger. I had wandered for days, only encountering savage hungry beasts stalking, seeking to preserve their life through the consumption of others. How I was like they. Was I becoming a packless wolf? One to trod icy reaches, eager eyes ever searching for the kill. The deep winding journey into these frosty plains peaks and mountains, ever ice, ever snow. This seemingly endless wandering mirrored my plunge into my own soul. If I did return, would I return intact? Did I truly seek to continue or was this yet another level of denial I had yet to shatter like glass? <br>
<br>
It was night again, I carefully edged my way down a slippery jagged ice mountain side. In the distance I heard my brothers, the hungry wolves. They were my companions. Quietly, patiently they followed me. Were they intrigued of this journey? Or was this a patient waiting for me to weaken, to be ripe and easy for their taking. I turned my eyes to one as he padded up softly in the night time snow, my breath frosting before me as our eyes met. Ceasing to pant he closed his maw, remaining still. We studied the depths of each other, how much did a simple beast comprehend? How much better or wiser was I really than he? He broke with my gaze, gracefully trotting off, I knew to join his brothers. <br>
<br>
I had no pack, no safety. The days taught me that perhaps I was wrong, while I heard other wolves from time to time, it was only this one that was ever attending me at a cautious distance. The fire would keep him away while I slept. He had yet to be so brave as to approach it. When sleep came, I was trembling, my tears were crystalline on my indigo face. Would this be my last time viewing this world? Inside I told myself, feebly, no, but deeper was an awakening horror, that I was indeed wrong. <br>
